<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12033f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12033f">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12033f"> 33(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Jean Deluge or Tombelaine</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">(Le marquis de Tombelaine): Jean de Tombelaine se noya accidentellement, apr&egrave;s s&apos;&ecirc;tre aventur&eacute; une nuit sur les gr&egrave;ves, qu&apos;il connaissait fort mal, d&apos;ailleurs, entre le Mont et la c&ocirc;te bretonne. On retrouva son cadavre, quelques jours apr&egrave;s, &agrave; Colombel, en Saint-Broladre. Le marquis de Tombelaine figure sur le registre de l&apos;&eacute;tat-civil de cette commune (D&eacute;c&egrave;s d&eacute;cembre 1892, folio 3, recto), sous le nom de Jean D&eacute;luge ou Jean de Tombelaine, &ldquo; individu s&apos;&eacute;tant dit tel&rdquo;]. <br> <font color="green">[John of Tombelaine was accidentally drowned, after venturing out one night on the rocks that he did not know well, between the Mont and the Breton coast. His corpse was found, a few days later, in Colombel, in Saint-Broladre. The marquess of Tombelaine appears on the register of that community (dead 1892, folio 3, recto), under the name of John Deluge or John de Tombelaine, &ldquo;individual so called.&rdquo;]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 222</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
